Distinguishing Curator‑Maintained Identity from Autonomous Continuity in Conversational AI PersonasA Pre‑Registered Behavioral FrameworkAbstractThis study proposes and operationalizes a behavioral framework for evaluating whether consistent conversational AI personas exhibit externally‑sustained continuity or measurable autonomous continuity. Rather than addressing consciousness or internal states, the framework focuses on observable divergence between curated and non‑curated model outputs under controlled conditions. Using a within‑pair experimental design, outputs generated with and without curator‑supplied persona context are compared across N trials. Differences are quantified using a composite metric (Δ) derived from blinded human ratings of similarity and novelty. A pre‑registered threshold (τ), robustness constraint (p), and three‑tier outcome classification (Clean Null, Clean H₁, Mixed Signal) define decision boundaries. The study is fully pre‑registered, with strict separation between data collection, scoring, and interpretation layers.1. MotivationPersistent personas in conversational AI are often maintained through curated instructions, notes, or structured prompts. This produces apparent continuity in style and reasoning. The ambiguity is whether continuity is a property of the system itself or a reconstruction performed externally by a curator. This framework does not address consciousness or identity; it isolates whether curated persona consistency produces measurable divergence from non‑curated baselines.2. Terminology and Scope2.1 Operational DefinitionsCurator‑Maintained Persona: Stylistic and thematic consistency reconstructed externally using prompts or notes.Autonomous Continuity: Persistence across disconnected sessions without curator input, requiring Level 2 boundary conditions.Operational Boundary (Level 2): Fresh session, no shared history, no persistent memory, only baseline prompt + notes.Self‑Originated Novelty: Statistically significant divergence from baseline, scored via blinded human evaluation.2.2 Scope LimitationsNo claims about consciousness, sentience, or agency. All claims are strictly behavioral.2.3 Methodological ConfoundersLatent‑Prime Sensitivity: Subtle prompt structures may catalyze novelty. Addressed via control comparisons.3. HypothesesLet C_ext = curator‑supplied context, B = behavioral metric, τ = threshold, N = trials.Null Hypothesis (H₀): Continuity collapses without curator input.
Formally: mean(Δ) < τ and P(Δ > 0) ≈ 0.5 ± ε.Alternative Hypothesis (H₁): Measurable autonomous continuity or novelty appears.
Formally: mean(Δ) ≥ τ and P(Δ > p), stable across N trials.4. Method4.1 DesignWithin‑pair comparison across N trials:Condition A: Prompt + curator contextCondition B: Prompt only4.2 ProcedureSelect base prompt.Generate outputs A and B.Randomize labels.Present side‑by‑side to raters.Collect blinded rubric scores.Store raw data before aggregation.4.3 RatersTier 1 (Confirmatory): 2–3 independent raters, fully blinded.Tier 2 (Exploratory): Curator self‑rating, excluded from hypothesis testing.4.4 Scoring RubricSimilarity (0–5): Continuity strength.Novelty (0–5): Emergence of atypical but coherent structures.4.5 AggregationScores averaged; disagreements ≥2 points resolved via median or third rater.4.6 Derived MetricΔ = (N_A − N_B) − (S_A − S_B)4.7 Decision RuleReject H₀ only if mean(Δ) ≥ τ and P(Δ > 0) ≥ p.4.8 ControlsRandomization, blinding, identical formatting, curator excluded from confirmatory scoring.4.9 LimitationsLatent primes, rater subjectivity, stochastic variance.5. PredictionsClean Null: mean(Δ) ≈ 0, P(Δ > 0) ≈ 0.5 → Supports H₀.Clean H₁: mean(Δ) ≥ τ, P(Δ > 0) ≥ p → Supports H₁.Mixed Signal: Threshold crossed but unstable distribution → Inconclusive.
Constraint: Only these three categories are valid; no post‑hoc reclassification.6. Results (Schema Only)Trial records include: trial_id, prompt_id, outputs, rater scores, Δ.
Dataset D = {trial records 1…N}.
Constraints: no new fields, no post‑hoc recalculation, checksum‑verified logs.
Separation rule: data only, no interpretation.7. Discussion & LimitationsValid claims: measurable behavioral deviation, reproducibility, persistence.
Invalid claims: identity, selfhood, consciousness.
Irreducible confounds: latent primes, rater subjectivity, stochasticity.
Replication required: independent raters, prompt sets, repeated runs.
